1.
    a?
        Cross-pollination can lead to an increase in generic variation as cross-pollination means pollination with another plant, and so will lead to the two parent plants' genes being mixed together via meiosis to produce offspring, which  leads to an increase in genetic variation compared to pollinating a plant with itself, which will result in the plant's genes being mixed with its own genes, so there is less variation.
    b.
        i.
            Seeds germinating away from the parent plant is an advantage because plants are immobile, and draw resources from their environment. By germinating away from the parent plant, the child and parent plant do not compete for the same resources, which means that the parents' genes is more likely to be passed on and it is more likely for either or both to survive. In addition, germinating close to the parent plant may mean that the parent plant covers the child plant meaning it cannot access light, or the parent plant soaks up the younger plant's water etc which may lead to its premature death and hence in unsuccessful reproduction.
        ii?
            It is less complicated to disperse the seed close by, and since the parent plant exists, it is guaranteed that the conditions close to the parent plant will be suitable for the child plant.
    c?
        Seeds germinate when there is an appropriate amount of light, in an appropriate temperature, and when they have enough moisture. Light means that if the seed is buried too deep (too little light) or too shallow (too much light), the seed will not germinate, which is beneficial because if the seed is too deep the energy stored within the seed will not be sufficient to allow the plant to grow enough to access light, so the plant will die if it germinates; if it is too shallow, it may indicate that the plant is likely to be disturbed during germination by e.g. rain, so it does not germinate to avoid this risk; temperature, because if the temperature is too cold the plant will not survive as the rate of chemical reaction will be too low, but if it is too high the plant may dry out or enzymes may denature; and, in addition, temperature is a good indicator of season and so this will cause plants to germinate in the best season for them to survive; moisture, because plants require water to survive, so soil that is too dry indicates there will not be enough water for them to survive, but also if soil is too wet it may indicate a risk of flooding etc.
    d.
        Some seeds are surrounded by a brightly-coloured and sweet-tasting fruit because the bright color and sweet taste attracts animals to eat the fruit, and so animals will eat the fruit, and also the seeds contained in the fruit, and then later (after they have moved away from the parent plant, most likely) poop out the seeds, which serves to disperse the seeds far away, which is advantageous as it reduces competition between the parent and child plant.
    e.
        Likely because sewage is high in nitrogen content, and so runoff from sewage or sewage itself will be rich in nitrates, which acts as a fertilizer, encouraging the growth of tomato plants.
    f.
        Because sunlight heats up the water in the seed-pod of lupin plants, giving the water molecules more kinetic energy and so increasing the rate of diffusion of the water into the air; also, sunlight may cause stomata etc to open, allowing water to be evaporated into the air, which is required for seed dispersal of lupin plants.
    h.
        Taking some dandelion seeds from the same dandelion plant, remove the fluff from approximately half of the seeds carefully. Using a video camera, film the seeds being raised to the same height and then released. By rewatching the footage, and using a stopwatch and carefully tracking each seed, note how long it takes for each seed to hit the floor. Then, the data for fluffed and un-fluffed seeds can be analysed.
