    c.
        i?
            The root hair cell has a high surface area by virtue of the root hair, which means water is taken up via osmosis faster. Water also leaves the root hair cell and goes into the rest of the plant via osmosis, as there is lower water potential in the rest of the plant. This maintains the concentration gradient between the soil and the root hair cell, so water is continually taken up via osmosis via the root hair cell and into the rest of the plant.
        ii?
            Water filling up the air spaces in the soil around the plant roots may wash away or severely reduce the concentration of and hence cause more energy to be required to take up mineral ions from the soil via active transport. This means less mineral ions will be available to the plant, which may impact the production of amino acids (mineral ions are required to produce amino acids), which are required to produce proteins, which are vital for growth and repair. Further, so much water being present may cause too much water to be taken up into the plant, causing plant cells to become turgid.
