5.
    a.
        The mass of fish caught by traditional fishing was higher than the mass of fish produced by fish farming from 1960 to at least 1980 if not 1990 for all three countries, and fish farming did not exceed traditional fishing until approximately 2010 for country C and fish farming never exceeded traditional fishing for country B. For all countries and for both methods, the mass of fish obtained increased with time. There was a very sharp increase in the growth of production of fish via fish farming at about 1980-1990 for country A, and mass of fish produced by fish farming continued to increase at that high rate until 2016. Mass of fish caught by traditional fishing also had a sudden increase in growth at a similar time for country A, but growth slowed at about 1995 before recovering somewhat in the next approximately 20 years. This seems to indicate there was a sudden increase in demand for fish at around 1980. This may be because of other factors like population growth, which in turn led to heavy investment in fish farming but also traditional fishing, or this may be because earlier investment in fish farming allowed for cheap fish production and hence caused a higher demand for fish as prices fell. The slight plateau in about 1995 can be explained perhaps as uncertainty in the future of traditional fishing in the face of fish farming. For countries B and C, traditional fishing grew continuously at approximately a constant rate, whereas there is only very slight growth in fish farming for country B and only a sudden increase in rate of growth recently for country C. This may indicate that country C only recently took up fish farming. Further, the very high mass of fish produced by both methods by country A in comparison to countries B and C, which produce comparatively very little fish even in traditional fishing, let alone fish farming, may indicate either that it has significantly higher population than countries B and C, so a significantly higher demand; or, more likely, country A is an exporter of fish whereas countries B and C are not. 
    b.
        To maximise production of fish, a fish farmer can:
        - pump antibiotics, antifungal medicine, and pesticides into where the fish is kept in order to stave off disease and pests
        - Keep the fish in a small, enclosed area to enhance the effectiveness of the above, and also to prevent fish from escaping, which obviously reduces yield, and to prevent fish from being eaten by predators
        - Put growth-stimulating substances such as growth hormone in the fish's food, in order to encourage growth of fish
        - Control the fish's food to be high in protein so they grow faster, especially when small
        - Not keeping predator and prey fish together
        - Omnivorous fish can be kept so that cheap feed such as unwanted parts of plants can be used
