    c?
        i.
            In solution A, the surrounding solution of the red blood cells has a higher water potential, so water enters the red blood cells via osmosis, causing them to rupture and burst. This results in a clear red solution. In contrast, for tubes B and C, the solution is either isotonic or has a lower water potential, causing either no net water movement via osmosis or net movement of water out of the red blood cells, which would cause the cells to shrivel. This results in a cloudy suspension as the cells remain intact.
        ii.
            
            In solution A, the surrounding solution of the red blood cells has a higher water potential, so water enters the red blood cells via osmosis, causing them to rupture and burst. So, no cells can be seen as they have ruptured. In contrast, for tubes B and C, the solution is either isotonic (tube B) or has a lower water potential (tube C), causing either no net water movement via osmosis (tube B) or net movement of water out of the red blood cells (tube C). The cells in tube C shrivel as water moves out of the red blood cells, causing the shrunken edges. There is no net water movement between the cells and the surrounding solution in tube B, so there is no effect on the cells.
    d?
        The blood would look exactly the same, except there would be a plasma layer that looks apparently larger as the blood has been diluted.